orization2star  aIn October 2008 the European Commission published its Proposal for a Consumer Rights Directive which puts forward far-reaching changes to the core of consumer contract law: Four current directives are to be replaced by a new, overarching piece of legislation and in doing so full harmonisation for the most part is to take the place of the minimum standard presently in force in the EU. Although a welcome initiative, the extent and possible effects of the Proposal have certainly brought a number of issues to the fore. In January 2009, legal experts from universities, practice and the civil service met to address the points raised by the Proposal and the question of the extent to which it can indeed contribute to the modernisation and harmonisation of European consumer contract law. The papers presented at this conference analysed, criticised and suggested improvements for the Proposal and are published in this volume.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConsumer protectionxLaw and legislationzEuropean Union countries. 0aContractszEuropean Union countries. 0aLawxInternational unification. 7aLAW / International.2bisacsh1 aBeale, Hugh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrownsword, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHowells, Geraint, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoos, Marco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMak, Vanessa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMicklitz, Hans-W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNordhausen Scholes, Annette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRiefa, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a